{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c391b2d2-16f8-4ebb-a7ea-0bae63897c58","content":"On macOS, the OS itself captures crash reports. Look here:\n\n1. **Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). They contain the stack trace, signal info, and loaded images.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./YourApp\n   ```\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, the `.ips`/`.crash` report will show native frames directly (no managed runtime), so the stack trace is usually straightforward to read.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ff194455-b107-485a-8d9f-82f370ea59e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":317},"id":"52e3c70b-48eb-4d77-865b-8ad41e8e2bbe","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:59:39.523Z","parentId":"812d0497-b4b4-43ed-9929-6d734b6e7dc8"}
